<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-409-606  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 409 606.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Information Executive  Spring 1990 v3 n2 p33(4).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>A framework for designing competitive information systems.andO;(includes a related article on creating an information system)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Newman, William A.; Brock, Floyd J.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Competitive Information Systems (CIS), also known as StrategicInformation Systems (SIS) have been in existence for more than 30years.andP;  Organizations choosing to create such systems must firstdevelop and understand a competitive framework for themselves andtheir rivals.andP;  Several methodologies for examining an industry incompetitive light, analyzing a company's external competitiveposition, and analyzing a company's own culture are examined.andO;These include Michael Porter's model, based on the Industry andCompetitive Analysis framework, for planning and operationsdesigned to shape a company's competitive strategy; Wiseman'sStrategic Option Generator for identifying competitiveopportunities, which is based on identifying strategic targets andthe strategic thrusts needed to reach them; King and Cleland'sinformation system for generating data to support strategicplanning; and Athos and Pascale's 7-S framework for analyzing afirm's internal structure.andP;  Multidimensional questions whichregard competitive structure and which are based on Cash's sixbasic competitive questions are presented: Who and where are thecompetitors? Is your business competitively structured? Is theright amount of money being spent on correctly focused competitiveapplications? Is there proper leadership for competitive activity?andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     CompetitionModelsBusinessMethodsInformation SystemsSystem Design.andO;Feature:   illustrationchart.andO;Caption:   Elements of industry structure. (chart)The Wiseman Strategic Option Generator. (chart)Creating an information system for competitive advantage. (chart)andM;</